Cross validation lasso was ran on the ordered and unordered datasets seperately.

The ordered model was then used on the non-ordered dataset and the non-ordered model on the ordered dataset to test their accuracy in predicting coverage.

set.seed(2)
# use ordered model on non-ordered data
ord4noord <- predict(cv.ord,newx = x_noord, s = cv.ord$lambda.1se, type="response")
rounded_scores <- round(ord4noord, digits = 0)
new <- cbind(cs_noord, rounded_scores)
length(which(new$covered==new$"1"))/nrow(new) # 78.424% accurate
## [1] 0.78424
# use non-ordered model on ordered data
noord4ord <- predict(cv.noord,newx = x, s = cv.noord$lambda.1se, type="response")
rounded_scores <- round(noord4ord, digits = 0)
new <- cbind(cs_ord, rounded_scores)
length(which(new$covered==new$"1"))/nrow(new) # 81.042% accurate
## [1] 0.81042

The results show that the model for the ordered data is 78.4% accurate in predicting coverage in the non-ordered data, and the model for non-ordered data is 81% accurate for predicting coverage in the ordered data.

Test accuracy of models in predicting coverage in their own datasets (ordered training for ordered test and unordered training for unordered test)

Each dataset was then split into test and training sets (nb, training set gives extremely similar model to the one for the whole dataset) to test the accuracy of the models to predict coverage in sets that have been ordered or not-ordered.

set.seed(2)
# ordered model to predict coverage in ordered sets
test <- sample(nrow(cs_ord), 25000) # randomly select rows to form the test set
test_set <- cs_ord[test, ]
training_set <- cs_ord[-test,]
xtraining        <- as.matrix(data.frame(training_set[,c(1:3,5:8)]))
xtest        <- as.matrix(data.frame(test_set[,c(1:3,5:8)]))

cv.ord_training <- cv.glmnet(xtraining, y=training_set$covered, alpha=1, family="binomial")
coef(cv.ord_training,s=cv.ord_training$lambda.1se)
## 8 x 1 sparse Matrix of class "dgCMatrix"
##                         1
## (Intercept) -2.914237e+01
## thr          2.629080e+00
## size         2.358128e+00

## entropy      .           
## N            2.698833e-04
## OR           2.417427e+01
## nsnps       -4.894708e-04

rounded_scores <- round(glm_scores, digits = 0)
new <- cbind(test_set, rounded_scores)
length(which(new$covered==new$"1"))/nrow(new) # 84.07% accurate
## [1] 0.84068
set.seed(2)

xtest.n        <- as.matrix(data.frame(test.n_set[,c(1:3,5:8)]))

cv.noord_training <- cv.glmnet(xtraining.n, y=training.n_set$covered, alpha=1, family="binomial")
coef(cv.noord_training,s=cv.noord_training$lambda.1se)

The results show that the model for ordered data is 84.07% accurate in predicting coverage in ordered sets, and that the model for non-ordered data is 79.88% accurate in predicting coverage in non-ordered sets.

Ordered test Non-ordered test
Ordered model 84.07 78.4

Why is the non-ordered model better at predicting the ordered test than the non-ordered test?

Baseline model

The number of snps is fixed (\(nsnps=100\)) and the threshold is fixed (\(thr=0.6\)). The baseline model we wish to improve in this section is \[log(\frac{p}{1-p})=log(\frac{size}{1-size})\] Where \(y=coverage\) and \(p=prob(y=1)\). Note that we do not know p, in which case this analysis would be a lot easier.

Claim 1: This baseline model is a good predictor of coverage in non-ordered sets.

Method: Fit this model using training set and predict accuracy using test set for NON-ORDERED data.

The training set had 1600 entries, the test set has 200 entries.

set.seed(2)
# fix threshold and nsnps for ordered and non-ordered
cs_ <- cs_ord[cs_ord$thr=="0.6" & cs_ord$nsnps=="100",] # 1800 entries
cs_noord <- cs_noord[cs_noord$thr=="0.6" & cs_noord$nsnps=="100",] # 1800 entries

# ensure size!=1 or logit=inf
cs_noord$size[cs_noord$size > 0.99999] <- 0.99999
cs_$size[cs_$size > 0.99999] <- 0.99999

# make test and training for non-ordered
test.n <- sample(nrow(cs_noord), 200) # randomly select rows to form the test set
test.n_set <- cs_noord[test.n, ]
training.n_set <- cs_noord[-test.n,]
xtraining.n        <- as.matrix(data.frame(training.n_set[,c(1:3,5:8)]))
xtest.n        <- as.matrix(data.frame(test.n_set[,c(1:3,5:8)]))
logitsize.n <- log(training.n_set$size/(1-training.n_set$size))

claim1_noord <- glm(covered ~ logitsize.n, data=training.n_set, family='binomial')
summary(claim1_noord)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = covered ~ logitsize.n, family = "binomial", data = training.n_set)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##      Min        1Q    Median        3Q       Max  
## -2.69533   0.00496   0.13036   0.92362   0.97006  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)   0.1152     0.1051   1.096    0.273    
## logitsize.n   0.9720     0.1224   7.940 2.03e-15 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)

##     Null deviance: 1628.6  on 1599  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 1275.6  on 1598  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 1279.6
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 8
# test out the accuracy of this model on the test unordered data
logitsize.n_test <- log(test.n_set$size/(1-test.n_set$size))
df.n <- data.frame(logitsize.n = logitsize.n_test)
glm_scores.n <- predict(claim1_noord, df.n, type="response")
rounded_scores.n <- round(glm_scores.n, digits = 0)
new.n <- cbind(test.n_set, rounded_scores.n)
length(which(new.n$covered==new.n$rounded_scores.n))/nrow(new.n) # 79.5% accurate
## [1] 0.795

How effective is this model for ordered datasets?

test <- sample(nrow(cs_), 200) # randomly select rows to form the test set
test_set <- cs_[test, ]
training_set <- cs_[-test,]
xtraining        <- as.matrix(data.frame(training_set[,c(1:3,5:8)]))

Claim 2: Improve accuracy of baseline model for ordered sets by including entropy as a predictor

Method: Run a glm on the ordered training set with logitsize and entropy as a predictor. Check the accuracy of predicting coverage in the ordered test set.
